nd","Huntingtondonshire, England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"en":{"1463–1508":"1463–1508","1462–1548":"1462–1548","1466–Female":"1466–Deceased","1459–1505":"1459–1505","1480–1548":"1480–1548","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1489–1559":"1489–1559","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1433–1503":"1433–1503","1462":"1462","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1503":"1503","1558":"1558","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1433":"1433","1466":"1466","1463":"1463","1508":"1508","February 1489":"February 1489","1505":"1505","1559":"1559","1548":"1548","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Huntingtondonshire, England":"England, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wolston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Woolston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woolston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wol(f)stan</i> (Old English <i>Wulfstān</i>, composed of the elements <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’ + <i>stān</i> stone).","habitational name from Wolston (Warwickshire), Woolstone (Buckinghamshire), or any of various places called Woolston, such as Woolston in West Alvington (Devon), Woolston in Warrington (Lancashire), and Woolston Hall in Chigwell (Essex). The Warwickshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfrīc</i> (genitive <i>Wulfrīces</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Buckinghamshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfsige</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Devon placename probably has the same etymology as the Buckinghamshire placename. The Lancashire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulf</i> (genitive <i>Wulfes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. The Essex placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfhelm</i> (genitive <i>Wulfhelmes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. There may have been some confusion with   Wollaston  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Wolston was born in 1463, in Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, her father, Sir Guy Wolston, was 31 and her mother, Margaret De Huntingdon, was 30. She married Sir Guy Abraham Sapcote in 1479, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1508, in her hometown, at the age of 45, and was buried in Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England."},"et":{"1463–1508":"1463–1508","1462–1548":"1462–1548","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1459–1505":"1459–1505","1480–1548":"1480–1548","1482–1558":"1482–1558","1489–1559":"1489–1559","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1433–1503":"1433–1503","1462":"1462","1482":"1482","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1503":"1503","1558":"1558","1459":"1459","1479":"1479","1489":"1489","1433":"1433","1466":"1466","1463":"1463","1508":"1508","February 1489":"veebruar 1489","1505":"1505","1559":"1559","1548":"1548","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Huntingtondonshire, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","